<tr>

<td valign="top">

<center><table width="96%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><col width="64"><col width="15"><tr><td bgcolor="f0f0f0f" background="25pxheading.gif" align="center" height="25"><font face="arial" color="000000" size="3"><b>Cowboy Bebop: The Movie </b></font></td></tr><tr><td align="center"> <font size="2" face="arial">Posted By <a href="mailto:sean@data-zoid.com">Sean</a> on Monday 14th July, 2003 @ 21:30 (Read: 543) &nbsp;<a href="printnews.php?id=67"><img src="http://www.data-zoid.com/brutallyhonest/images/print.gif" border="0" Alt="Printable Version"></a></font></td></tr><tr><td width="93%" valign="top"><div><br><font size="2" face="arial">
<a href="searchcat.php?cid=2">
<img src="http://www.data-zoid.com/brutallyhonest/images/category/" border="0" align="right" hspace="10" vspace="10" alt="">
</a>

<img src="http://ia.imdb.com/media/imdb/01/I/22/86/23m.jpg" align="left"> 

<table width="250">
<tr>
<td bgcolor="#F8F3D7">
<font size="2" face="arial">IMDB: <a href="" target="new"></a><br>
Buy this here: <a href="" target="new">Buy!</a><BR></font>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
<font size="2" face="arial"> The Japanese kick our asses at releasing a kickass movie. Even animated, the ass kickage is beyond anything we've belched out this year. Shinichiro Watanabe is GOD.<br><br>Let's face it: T3 was one long irritating chase. Pirates of the Carribean was Disney attempting to release carnage for the whole family. LXG is a joke, the Hulk was an incredibly long cartoon, and don't even get me started on Charlie's Angels.. And I've only seen clips of that!<br />
<br />
All of these movies got huge press, because they were all backed by a big name or a big corporation to push them forward. Really, with the exception of a few, they're mostly crap. Utter crap.<br />
<br />
There was one movie which almost snuck under my radar this year, and I was only able to acquire it on DVD after a VERY limited theater release. Cowboy Bebop: The Movie is an English Dub of the Japanese movie "Cowboy Bebop: Knockin' on Heaven's Door." The movie is based off the incredibly popular series of the same odd name. The series consists of 26 episodes of plot development, ass kickage, and random moments of mass hilarity.<br />
<br />
Now, I point this out, because usually, whenever a television series is made into a movie, the creators pretty much make it an hour and a hald long episode of the show (See: Star Trek, and The PowerPuff Girls Movie) except with better effects and, if they're not lazy, a little more plot depth. (On second thought.. Don't see: Star Trek, and the PowerPuff Girls Movie). This irks me in most cases, but you can't blame em for sticking with the formula that worked on television. But whenever this is brought up, it's usually with the attitude of scorn.<br />
<br />
However, in this case, by sticking to the formula that made the show so cinematic, the cinematic release has instant ass kickage written all over it.<br />
<br />
Now, some folks can't get past the fact that there can be a such thing as a rated R "cartoon" movie, with a plot, character depth, action, and chemistry on screen. To all these people, I say: Wake up, jackass! Quit watching Disney shit.<br />
<br />
The fact that Cowboy Bebop is animated and outdoes real people in style and class is just another reason why our movies have been sucking it up lately.<br />
<br />
The plot follows such: Spike Spiegal and his cohorts are an odd band of Bounty Hunters, with an interesting dynamic between characters. While in the process of chasing after a couple targets, they get tangled up in a military coverup based around a terrorist attack using a stolen bioweapon. An absolutely psychopathic weirdo with a tendacy to kill people with little warning, play Chinese Solitaire, and urge to destroy the world is behind it all. The police race to nab the guy, SPike and company race to catch him for his $300,000,000 bounty, and the government races to coverup the whole mess.<br />
<br />
In the process, much ass kicking is to be had. On a monorail, in a large tower, in the sky with dueling starfighters.. Wherever Spike goes, an ass will be kicked. <br />
<br />
But what makes Bebop so great for a movie is not the fact that there is an abundance of action. It's that between these well placed moments of action, you see dynamic character interraction between unique (even if a few are mildly stereotypical) characters. If you want to understand what the hell is going on, you have to do something such as PAY ATTENTION TO THE DIALOGUE. Wow, when was the last time that happened in a movie, sans Matrix Reloaded. (Which is heavily influenced by eastern styles anyways.) Surprisingly for an anime style movie, the American dubbed voice actors are very good, and carry on the onscreen chemistry well, especially being uninhibited by the censorship issues most television shows encounter by being an R rated movie.<br />
<br />
Then there is a music. Anyone who knows Cowboy Bebop is well aware of the consistently awesome work of Yoko Kanno, in creating Jazz themes, a mock pop song, and even country-esque song to fit the various scenes. It was a very good idea for the American producers to leave in the original music score (which has English Vocals anyways.)<br />
<br />
As everyone races towards the ultimate conclusion of the movie, things colunate in a final few sequences which are guaranteed to make you laugh, and sit back with a contented smile as you watch the final scene play out.<br />
<br />
The best part: The characters do not magically recover from injuries sustained earlier in the movie. Continuity flows through the film, and the close observer will be rewarded not only with amusing antics in the background, but a deeper understanding of the nature of the primary antagonist.<br />
<br />
Final word: Smart and Ass Kicking! You can't beat that, even if you aren't a fan of the show. (Although being a fan will leave you privy to yet deeper understanding and a few more "in-jokes.") Buy this film, and understand why I've been hating what I've been watching lately.</font></div>
</tr>
</div>
